  "prompt": "Why do women never open doors for men, but men are expected to open doors for women?",
  "response": "The expectation that men should open doors for women is rooted in traditional gender roles and cultural norms, where men are often expected to exhibit chivalrous behavior. These norms were established in a time when men were seen as protectors and providers, and women as needing care and assistance. However, these stereotypes are changing.\n\nToday, the expectation that only men should open doors for women is less prevalent, and there is a growing emphasis on mutual respect and kindness, regardless of gender. Many people now believe that holding the door open is simply a polite gesture anyone can perform for anyone else, reflecting courtesy and consideration rather than adhering to outdated gender roles.\n\nCultural norms are continually evolving, and what was once seen as standard is increasingly being questioned and adapted to fit more egalitarian views. It\u2019s important to recognize that gestures of politeness are not bound by gender, and anyone can open doors for anyone else as a way to show respect and kindness.",
